The interest rate will increase and the bull market (growing market) will stumble, return on bonds will increase and the economy will go into recession.
That's what we know.
What we don't know is how long it will happen and how long it will last.
In the economy, history gives little indication of time frame.
After the first increase in the interest rate, the recession occurred in only 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The fact that the Federal Reserve is aggressive in increasing interest rates is often, although not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That is why US central bank officials stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when the interest rate starts to rise but on the trajectory of the time needed for normalisation.
Indeed, there are multiple variables at stake.
However, in the end, market players may find that all the excitement about the interest rate increase has been exaggerated.
"The first increase in the interest rate decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the era "cheap money," said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, on a note addressed to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal levels, but still small, to constitute the seismic shock that everyone seems to be afraid of.
But it cannot be said that there will be no effect.
Here is how several sectors of the economy could react, building on historical trends:
Given the situation faced by the market in recent months, anticipation of the increase in the interest rate may make things volatile for a while.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"It seems that there is a trend that the return on capital will stagnate for 12-24 months after the first growth, which may reflect again the phase out of monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed increases.
More specifically, over the last 35 years, the market has suddenly increased - by about 14 percent - moving towards an increase in the interest rate, quite invariable in the period of 250 days after (average climb of 2.6%) and then returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by the head strategist of Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche said the impact on the shares tended to become more pronounced later in the interest rate cycle and the benefits are beginning to decrease.
The recession is a reality of economic life, but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that did not exist before and could speed up a recession.
In particular, the gross domestic product will approach its historical minimum point for an increase in the Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases after 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Although in the second quarter of 2015, the value was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
The increase in the interest rate in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question "if this time it is different," Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing all year for a Fed growth decision, all eyes being set on this week's meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in the interest rate during this meeting, term transactions show a probability of only 25%.
"In our study after 1950, all interest rate growth cycles so far have been in a super profit growth cycle, with GDP eclipsed peaks before the recession very quickly after recovery began," the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery after the worst recession in the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
The fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an increase in the interest rate and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for shares when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it appears that benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate growth cycle, the return on bonds is falling immediately," Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategies are of the opinion that these interest rate increases will bring profitability closer between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
High-efficiency bonds do better in such an environment, although "we are still cautious about forcing profitability," Kathy Jones, a fixed income analyst at Schwab, said in a review.
Interestingly, Jones believes that the markets have already adapted to the expectations of Fed policy.
"Besides the dollar's power and the expected decline in inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the perspective of a more rigorous monetary policy," Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the return curve is fairer, the spread of the average credit interest rate has expanded and volatility has increased - all market characteristics when the Fed tightens policy.
Generally speaking, companies operating mostly in the US will benefit from the interest rate increase and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will suffer because the dollar growth will lead to the increase in their products in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
