At the most expected meeting in recent years, the Federal Reserve policy makers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany meal to decide whether the time has come to increase a key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank meeting room, a mural painting of the United States will be seen.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank received a double task from Congress: maximising the employment rate in the US and maintaining price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is ready to be debated by the unprecedented incentive provided by the near zero short-term interest rate in force as of the end of 2008.
Although most data indicate a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials of adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to increase the interest rate, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed's decision, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists polled by Bloomberg recently anticipated an increase in interest rates this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to postpone, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a fall in the stock exchange if the Fed increases the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228,89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599,85.
The wind has been triggered by expectations that Fed decision-makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for the Fed to increase the interest rate at this point," Lonski said.
If the Fed makers were to do so, "they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets".
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed to be about to increase the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards slowly tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the force of US recovery.
Yellen said in spring and early summer that he expected an increase in the interest rate this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was strong this year.
Unemployment dropped to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wages showed signs of growth.
And while inflation has continued to fail to reach the annual goal of the central bank, Fed decision-makers said that a key reason was the temporary effect of falling oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tension on the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to enter fibrillations later this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average dropped by 16% below the record peak reached in May, as investors feared that slowing down the Chinese economy would bring down global growth.
The market has somewhat recaptured this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below the May peak.
For Fed decision-makers, the turmoil in the market is added to the complex calculation of the interest rate increase moment.
"Without what has happened in the financial markets and news about the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer at the hearing," said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former official Fed.
Now he expects to wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a great deal of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy and they almost have no data to base on after the events in China," Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the main interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The mere reference of the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, in 2013 that the Fed could "narrow" its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department of the welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of Richmond Federal Reserve Bank, said this month that "Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic bases."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate increase, provided as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia caused the Fed to reduce the reference rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "Despite the implications of limited identification for the development of the US," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to the fallout.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate committee, said.
The last hectic period is nowhere near that level, he said.
"We certainly do not want to be in a situation of fear of an increase in interest rates because the markets are upset," said Posen, President Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds its double mandate and does not mention financial stability and until something changes in this respect, I do not think that it should take premature action.
