Weight reduction surgery could be useful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those undergoing non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralise mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgeon, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the hunger sensation and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proved effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight measurement relative to height, is considered normal within the range 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your IMC by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in sleeve - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in surgical patients decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments against diabetes remained almost at the same level, i.e. 29.
Of those who had surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes mellitus was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and bad LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group”, the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin level of A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it remained at about 8%.
However, this improved “blood glucose control” – reflected by improved levels of haemoglobin A1c – did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy arm, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), experienced greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and were more likely to have complete diabetes remission (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of high-weight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had bariatric surgery were approximately 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared with a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it says that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long until we urge people to take this seriously," she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have shorted out their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely hard to get back to normal.
