"A child doesn't think he's hurting her," Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are perfumed ones.
Strawberry-flavored hand cleaners, grape, orange are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's very concentrated alcohol," said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poison center at Kansas University Hospital, for Channel Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand cleaners in accessible places, and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-flavored hand sprays at school, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had alcohol levels 179, twice as high as the threshold at which an adult is legally considered under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, a doctor at the emergency room who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was babbling and couldn't walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage, as the girl fell and hit her head because of alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic wet products or wipes and leave the hand detergent out of the reach of children.
