FriendsFest: the comedy series that taught us important lessons about male friendship
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, as the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching the peak in the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the main cause of death in men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the problem, the Campaign against Unfortunate Life (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, wanting to question the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the struggle towards the success of this challenge.
A recent study conducted on more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends "with a healthy mood", his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends reduces the likelihood of mental disorders by half.
Of course, for friendship to work, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even though it is really isolation that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which affects our mental health even more deeply.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that it focused attention on this idea.
The characters were not defined by the workplace but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when they watch football in the comfortable armchairs and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that it is known that men can associate with this situation, even though they often avoid fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: ..."My role in listening to people with suicidal and depressed tendencies has shown how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often people who appeal to us do not feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to handle yourself is powerful, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you speak openly about problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term psychological adaptation mechanisms.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
No matter how much objective, external intervention helps, through the phone, people in times of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you attend this weekend at the FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the full play of the set to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends for coffee in Central Perk.
Or even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship might make.
