On Wednesday, the government approved the "National Strategy on Immigration for 2015-2018" and the "Active Plan for the Year in progress", documents considered to be "another stage Romania is undertaking in its efforts to modernise the process of managing immigration on national territory", according to a press release.
The source cited shows that the strategy aims to manage immigration effectively, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
Given the problems faced by the states in Romania's immediate neighbourhood, measures are envisaged for unitary and coherent management of situations caused by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants on Romania's territory, due to political, social, economic or military crisis.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time they will pay special attention to citizens from states with potential migrationist or that may harm national security," adds the mentioned source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivation of the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuation and increase in intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of citizens of third countries on the territory of Romania and proper application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania of third-party citizens who respond to the needs of employment, promoting the access of third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciates that this is "a means of establishing concrete activities that will lead to the creation of a flexible system for stopping the growing migration phenomenon".
Romania, in a European top on the labour market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria registered the highest increase in total labour costs among the Member States of the European Union in the second quarter of the year, compared to the similar period in 2014, according to data published Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to employer staff expenditure.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total labour cost increased by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third in the EU to increase labour costs
The largest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly labour cost fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The advance of labour costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to an increase in the hourly cost of labour in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania registered a 5.8% advance on the hourly labour cost.
