Greater migrations
Romania is not and will not be ready for what is to come.
What about Europe?
I say it from the beginning, clear and clear: the 7000 refugees that Romania should and should naturalize are, in itself, an insignificant number, but huge compared to the ability of the Romanian state to manage such a project.
For Romania, even the voluntary quota proposed by Bucharest, amounting to about 1500 souls, goes far beyond our good intentions of solidarity with the European Union expressed in recent months.
Certainly, if those migrants even agree to settle in our localities, the chances of integrating them quickly into Romanian society are extremely low.
I'm sure they'll be the first to lose patience.
Parasited by the underworld and paralyzed by a venal political class, the Romanian state proves impotent in all areas.
The failure to integrate the gypsies is just a trivial example.
Besides, governments of every color have not been able to absorb European funds, make roads, kindergartens or modern schools, provide decent healthcare, clean up dirt on the street, create honorable paid jobs or keep their own young generation at home.
Why would refugees settle in another fleeing country?
But what brings great wonder is especially the hypocrisy with which such a crisis is dealt with.
First of all, we are dealing with the belligerent hypocrisy of the strong states of the EU, which are most generous when it comes to sharing problems with smaller countries.
Then comes the fearful hypocrisy of Romanians who, although they have millions of relatives scattered all over the world, do not yet accept the other - of another language, of another religion, of another blood.
Probably afraid of someone stealing his national being.
After all, there is also a hypocrisy of many migrants, who, although they only invoke the horrors of war as a reason for their departure, accept no other destination for the exodus than Germany or the Nordic countries.
But not all refugees are Syrians, and there is no war in Pakistan.
Furthermore, the simplistic way in which the crisis is analysed can only be mocked.
The causes must be eliminated, some argue, and by relying strictly on the book of political fairness, they demand peace and investment for migrants' countries of origin.
But there is peace in Romania, and even once in a while, some foreign capital enters the national economy - but that does not prevent tens of thousands of Romanians from leaving their country every year.
Why is he leaving?
In this crisis, the European Union has revealed itself to us as an ankylosed, divided and obsolete construction.
I deplored the fact that Romania is not able to invent a country project, but, look, the EU doesn't have any future plans either.
