EXCLUSIVE: A meeting that breaks your heart.
At the age of 20 he received a courageous gift: biological parents
Lost in the hospital in unclear conditions, in the dark of the 1990s, when she had only two months of life, little, sickly and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years as adoption was vaguely regulated, a young girl who had gone out, now a blonde and beautiful girl, met again the day before yesterday in Iasi with the biological parents from a village of the county, after almost two decades when no one knew anything about the others.
Crina will be 20 years old these days, and her adoptive parents in Palermo thought to give their beloved daughter an amazing and courageous gift: a visit to Romania, to Iași, in order to get to know her unclear past.
"The newspaper of Iași", which witnessed efforts to search for the family of origin after a few very vague clues, witnessed these encounters that practically break your heart.
The story of reporters, the emotions of moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are really moving and overwhelming.
The story of the Lily begins 20 years ago in the town of Iași Ruginosa, when she was only two months old.
Then, due to a health problem, the girl had to be hospitalized in the city.
At home there began to be misunderstandings between parents, and the mother had to appear her home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
He stopped the girl, and I haven't known anything since.
"When I found out she was in the hospital, it was too late," remembers grieving Alina, the girl's biological mother.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pașcani, and at the same time the girl's father, Costica Balcan, went to work in Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives would part forever.
They couldn't find Crina at the hospital.
After admission, Lily's father went to work in another locality, and returned six months later.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and the father, when he returned, never found her.
It must have been almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"She must have thought she was abandoned," tells a granddaughter of the family.
Due to financial problems, Grandma was unable to come with Crina to Iași, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one else has been interested in the fate of the child during this time, it was taken over by the Directorate General for Social Assistance and Child Protection Iasi, who then gave it to the Plasmation Centre in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more easily regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center was found by the Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but couldn't.
They fell in love on the spot with blonde Crina, and after some time she would move with them to Italy.
The little girl had already done almost two years, while the adoption formalities took place.
When I saw Crina, I felt like she was our girl.
"As if my wife had given him life," she says smiling Salvadore, the adoptive father, as he grabs the girl's fragile hand in his hand.
In the country, the parents of the Lily, Alina and Costica, continued their search separately, each where they could.
The father asked the Rusty authorities, but received no answer as to where his child might be.
The police then told her that she may be dead, but in Iasi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the courthouse she was away in Italy, in Palermo.
And conditions to look for it I never had.
We prayed to God that it would be okay.
I thought about her all those years ago, but there were no possibilities to walk, to find her.
"It's hard," the Lily's biological mother tells us with tears in her eyes.
Even though the years have passed, the parents of Rusinos have not been forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past links her to Romania.
I was a little girl when I found out.
I think I was five or six years old.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my parents in Romania," Crina said.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March of this year, Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim, director of the Regional Centre for Prevention, Evaluation and Drug Adviser Iași, was contacted by an acquaintance from Italy, who explained Salvadore's desire to find the Lilie's biological family.
And the search only started with one name.
After the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I had just received a name, Balcan Costica, then the town Ruginosa.
Soon I had an activity with the city hall there, and I could ask if there was a name in the village.
Then they gave me some indication, except the person they found wasn't the one they wanted.
"It took us about a month to find the girl's biological father," Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim explains.
In total, it took more than three months for the authorities to find Costica and Alina, especially since each had a place of residence in another locality.
We started the work somewhere in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of biological parents and discussions.
"Then we set a first meeting for September," Romica Ichim added.
In the past weekend, Alina and Costica first saw their lost girl in the hallways of the hospital in Iași, 20 years ago.
The father, excited, could barely contain his tears, and his hands trembled constantly.
He barely has a few words with the people around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn't even sleep.
He was all excited, shaking.
"To see your child after all these years, there is something," says a niece, who came with Costica from Rusinoasa.
Lilie meeting with biological mother and brother
In talks with his daughter, who is going to study at a well-listed university in Italy, Costica Balcan told him, among other things, that if she ever wanted to return to him in the village, she could come quietly: she could give him some sheep, goats, to find a boy from the village and build a household.
My mom's nervous too, she's crying, and she hardly thinks anything like this can happen to her.
I'm very excited.
I never thought anything like this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've been thinking these years, I've been hoping, but I never thought I could be like this.
They're very excited.
If only he could forgive me.
I hope we visit each other in the future.
"I hope we can keep a bond," tells us with great tears on Alina's cheeks, Lily's mother, while holding a napkin tight in her hand.
In him she still hides her tears, from happiness, because soon she will see her face after so much time.
On the other side, Crina, who will be only a few days away, this month, 20 years old, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she sketched a vague idea about her biological parents.
He thinks they're young, but now before the meeting he's trying to gather his thoughts, because he has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
But my parents are the ones who raised me after all.
It'll be a nice date, a wonderful experience.
"I hope to have a beautiful memory of them, because now there are so many things to say," Crina confesses.
First family reunion in Iasi
In the Unirii Square, under the early autumn sky, the family of Ruginosa again joins their destiny with their daughter in Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, finishing high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
They no longer divide borders or countries, but only one barrier: that of the tongue.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian local owner in the centre of Iasi, easily crossed.
Those who managed to make this meeting possible say it is the first such event done, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do so again.
It's the first event of its kind organized by such an emotional charge, and I'm glad to be a success.
We, at the Centre, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with the users, the drug addicts.
But we're trying to give society back something good.
"If I am requested for such an event again, I will do so with great love," says Romica Ichim, director of the Regional Centre for Prevention, Evaluation and Drug Adviser Iași.
Behind him, the Balcans, with Crina in the middle, walk away by telling stories.
They understand: they have a lot to say to each other.
