Constantin Brâncuși was born on 19 February 1876, in Hobița, a small village in Pestișani commune, Gorj county, at the foot of the Carpathians.
He is the fifth child of Maria and Radu Nicolae Brâncuși.
Although he came from a wealthy peasant family, Brâncuşi leads a modest life, but one of which will collect the landmarks that will guide his late artistic vision.
Remembering his childhood and the places he grew up, the artist would confess, in a meeting with Petre Țuțea, in Paris, in 1933: "At that time life was beautiful and harmonious.
For millennia, people lived, happily, a patriarchal life.
Everything went smoothly from one season to the next.
And do you know why things have changed?
The civilization of the great city has come to us.
Brâncuși's childhood, however, was far from idyllic.
One of the moments spent in these first years of life is highly suggestive of the combination of purity and violence that characterized the future sculptor's years in his hometown.
The moment is reproduced in the work "Brancusi. A biography", written by Alexandru Buican.
In 1879, Constantin Brâncuși was 3 years old.
In the autumn of that year, when the cheese was made, following those who taste the liquid to see if the process was going well, Brâncusi caught a moment of general inattention.
He fills his palms with henry and drinks unbreathed.
He falls in his sleep almost instantly.
The first people don't notice until a few minutes later.
My mother panics, then goes into hysteria, thinking her son died.
Towards the evening, when the father, Radu, returns from the vineyard accompanied by the fiddlers, he sees from afar the desperate signs of those who wait for him with their breath.
The party's turning into mourning.
Father's already thinking about burying.
However, one finds it good to call Baba Brândusa, a doctor and servant of the Brancus.
Brandusa checks the baby's breath, then puts horse dung under his nose, gathered around.
The baby sneezes heavily.
People applaud.
While the boy is allowed to sleep on his drunkenness, with joy, the party with the fiddlers continues with even more force.
The next day, father and son meet in the orchard.
Radu Brâncuși has Constantine gather some rods and bring them to him.
The father places his child upside down and, with the rods brought by the boy, beats him to remember.
And while he feels the sting of the blows, little Brâncuși has the revelation that the world can be seen from a different perspective and that things around him can appear upside down.
Especially the position of the sun, different from the well-known one, makes him wonder, as he would admit in his old age, if the astral itself was participating in his disorder.
Could the sun have been as troubled as his father by what had happened to him?
